Conclusions 
The equality of the three-dimensional light-front expression for the current,
lccur , and the corresponding four-dimensional BS expression, BScur ,
has been known for a long time. However, this result is not very
practical for calculational purposes as both the light-cone vertex function,
defined by curop , and the potential generating the light-cone wave
function, quasipot , are represented by infinite series even if the
underlying BS kernel  is simple. In addition, it has so far not been noticed
that between these two operators there is a direct connection (even though they
are given by series); namely,  can be obtained from  by the
procedure of gauging if the latter is properly defined in terms of two-time
Green functions.  A simple and natural definition of gauging in this paper is
summarised by defgaug  and gaugG0 , and makes the last statement
clear.  Our
definition of gauging enables us to construct the current operator corresponding
to any term of the series of quasipot . In particular, we have given the
explicit expression for the gauge invariant current [LO  and LOintcur ]
corresponding to the first term of quasipot . This expression can be used,
for example, in studies of one-particle exchange models.  Finally, we have shown
how to account perturbatively for the remainder of the terms in quasipot ,
by explicit consruction of the current in the NLO [NLOcur ]. Close
examination shows that all terms in NLOcur  are important for current
conservation, which is a result of cancellation between their longitudinal
parts.


The perturbation theory presented in this paper, in particular the expression of
NLOcur , could be applied, for example, to the calculation of meson cloud
effects on the electromagnetic form-factors, which are known to be important
. Although a similar program for the NJL model has been
demonstrated in Ref. , this should also be done in the light-front
approach. In this case, first the NLO potential  should be constructed
to incorporate one meson exchange in all possible ways within the LO model.
Next, such a  should be gauged in order to derive the meson exchange
electromagnetic current operator, , etc.

The gauge invariant perturbation theory proposed in this note is not
specific to the light-cone approach and can, for example, be 
applied to the spectator approach. The spectator potential
corresponding to the example of cross  reads
 
where  is the product of the single particle propagator  and the
spectator on-mass-shell  function. Currents would again be given in LO
by LO  and in NLO by NLOcur , however, rather than gauging the
equal-time light-cone propagators, one would gauge the on-mass-shell propagators
instead.





 
